description: A plain grey mushroom, fairly common in the spring. Often hard to tell from the C. glacialis, but very different in microscopic details.
Unknown Inocybe, never quite got the scope. I kept putting off the Inocybes, using the scope time to id other ’shrooms, and just never got around to this one…

One of the few large fleshy fungus we found plenty of, except for the B. pinophilus… Rather unremarkable white hygrophorus. It does grow with a partial veil, although it breaks at a very young age. But in the second photo here, you can see this.

Fairly common purple hygrophorus of the mountains. The one key feature of these is that they have a fiberous partial veil, but that it fades quickly as the stipe grows. The second photo here is a cap young enough to actually display evidence of this veil.

Dr. Desjardin was kinda excided to see this one, he said it was the first time found in ten years or so. It was called Helvella californica in his notes, and he remarked that it is now a different name, it was found to not match well with Helvella or Gyromitra. I forget which new name for the genus he mentioned, and he couldn’t remember the new species name. But there is a note in Arora’s MD that G. californica is a synonym for H. californica, so I have put this observation here.

If I find the new species name at some point, I’ll update these observations.

Given how he remarked that this was a rare sighting, kinda brings into question my other observation of this species from May. But those did have whitish wrinked backs, behind the brick red fertile surface. Although those did look more like Gyromitra and this one does look more like a Helvella, who knows. But it does bring up the fact that I shouldn’t have been so quick to just photo the other observation material, and toss it out.

But there is only so much you can do I guess, in our busy lives…
Only one found, and fairly dried out, sorry I couldn’t get a better one for a shot here…

Found on the last day, across the street from the field campus. This species has evolved to not come above ground, but it stays underground. The cortina never opens on these, unless old and disturbed, even though the spores are dropped by the gills onto the closed veil.

A small collection of unknown Corts. There were others, but I was concentrating on getting photos of known species I hadn’t photo’ed before. It would be nice to be able at some point in the future get species names on corts like this. It is getting annoying after years of doing this to be so dismissive of corts and getting an id.

A fairly common species that will come up right after the snow melts, usually only seen within days of snow melt in an area. But it is extreemly variable, and just a dull collection of browns and greys, and kinda hard to know it is what you have. Usually up there for me, it took looking at the spores to know that it was what it was.

Found on the last day, just across the street from the field campus. These were only seen one other time in the past ten years up there. Some others were also found that afternoon, but these were the best samples. The difference here from the C. auriantiaca is the surface of the cap.
These were the only two found up there, and the only time I have found these. I can finally see the difference between these and C. subsculpta.

These were common enough this time, most people found one or more. Not sure if I would say there were lots up there, but they were one of the the more common ones found. But this means that about 2 dozen people looking for a week found about 40 caps, maybe. It was a pretty sparse year for fungus in general.

Again this is just B. pinophilus until the new species is published, and then should be probably B. rexvernus.

This is a basidiomycetes that looks like an ascomycetes, but it is small resupinate fungus. The fungus here is the small bright orange cup-like discs on the branch bark. The other green stuff is lichens… and this should be part of Lichen Observer.

Looking at the microscopic details, you can see the basidia, and the basidio-spores. The spores are large, globose and deeply ornamented, so they are pretty easy to tell what it is.

One of the mushrooms that I was able to id with microscopic details this time, oooh, progress. The quality of the mushroom, the surface of the cap, the veil on the stipe, and in the end the germ pore in the spores id’ed this as A. praecox. But this part of the A. praecox group, which is pretty variable. The germ pore in the spores I tried to photograph, although I am not good at that yet, but you can kinda see it in the photo of the spores.

Id’ed by Dr. Desjardin. These get the plain brown mushroom award from me. These are soo plain, soo brown, soo laking in features, even after seeing them, and this photo, I still wouldn’t be able to id them if I saw them again.
These were the only samples ever seen of this species in the 25 years of the course up there. Usually a fall species, and never seen in the spring.
Id’ed by Dr. Desjardin.

Another species id’ed by me from microscopic details. Got much better at that this time up there… But these were id’ed by the nodulous spores, which were unique from all the spores I took a look at up there. The spores for these are almost like fat rectangles, with bumpy projections at each end. I think Dr. Desjardin refered to them as “booted” spores. Also the disc of the cap is smooth, although I thought the cap was shaggy, but it was one of those, “but not that shaggy” things, so it is called smooth. That id’ed it as I. albodisca.

An asci id’ed by – me! Using microscopic details, of course, there isn’t enough to this little asci to get anything but microscopic details. The main detail is spore shape, which they have these long thin cylindrical spores. The cups here are on these small thin stipes, which also seperates it from other tiny little colorless grey cup fungus.

This along with A. lobata (3498), D. virgineus (3501), and another tiny grey cup fungus that I didn’t id, made a group of microscopic fungus that I gathered in the bog. I showed them to Dr. Desjardin, which caused him to yell at me – “Stop bringing me fungus that I can’t see with my naked eyes!”.

Some people were excited to see these. I was told they are fairly rare, and never seen below 7,000 feet of elevation, or something like that. We were almost at 7,000 feet, since we had to go up from the Yuba pass to find snow banks melting, and the snow bank fungus.

One of the characters of these are the pink-orange colored caps. But by the time they got back to camp, the pinkish color seems to have faded a bit. So, I include a second photo here of the same samples, taken in the field at lunch time, which shows more of the pinkish color when they were fresh and still damp.

This one confused me, it looks a lot like the H. marzuolus, but I was told it is different. THe main macro feature I guess is the smell, these are indistinct, slightly fungal, really just not smelly. But the H. marzuolus is supposed to have a strong smell of mice cages, or I guess gerbal cages. There was one sample of H. marzuolus found this week, but I didn’t see it, so I didn’t get a chance to compare. Also looking in Largent’s Hygrophorus of CA, the spores are supposed to be different size and shape between the two. But the H. marzuolus disappeared before I could check that also.

A few of these were brough in this year, but still not able to compare enough to be able tell the difference between these and H. marzuolus in the future. But they both seem to be fairly rare mushrooms, that maybe it doesn’t matter than much. I’ll try to let it go.
Id’ed by Dr. Desjardin.
An underground (hypogeous) fungus, there were a few found this time. A number of people brought rakes with them to give it a try. This one is an asci, and the only hypogeous asci found this time.

These were id’ed by — Me! The caps are very small and the backsides are “hairy” like other Dasyscyphus. But these are colorless, which puts it into two difference species that have been seen up there before. But these have lanceolate paraphases (hee-hee – if you are into microscopic details of ascis that actually makes sense), so that makes these D. virgineus.

We had a few people this year that got into finding the really little stuff. Along with the lack of lots of the big stuff, made for some unique stuff found this time, like this one.

This looks kinda like D. bicolor, but the “hairs” on the back side of the small cups are smaller and don’t come around to the top side. So it doesn’t have that “blinking eyelash” look that D. bicolor does. Dr. Desjardin took this and looked at the spore size, and the thickness of the cell walls in the hairs, and made the id here.

This is a very very small sessile (no stipe (stem)) fungus that I found on a rotting log in the boggy area, also just under water. You have to look close to see the fungus, it is on the bottom side of the wood here, that I sliced off the rotting log, towards the left side. The fruiting body here it only large enough to have 4-5 gills.

Dr. Desjardin id’ed this as Arrhenia, and A. lobata was seen up there in the past, but not for a long time. Also the notes on A. lobata state that it should be seen in among mosses, and here it was on rotting wood. So, this might not be A. lobata, but another Arrhenia, but it matches the species in the other ways, just not the habitat notes.

Second image taken through a mounting scope.

description:
While out in the garden today I observed a struggle of life and death. A millipede,Tylobolus claremontus(?), was being attacked by another creature as shown above. I was unsure which was attacking which until I separated the two and the black and yellow attacker searched for the millipede again and essentially grabbed it by the throat and then wrapped its body around the head. I separated them again, this time leaving the predator near the tail of the millipede. The
predator searched briefly and then crawled along the entire length of its prey and again attacked the head area.

This was my second millipede of the day, having spotted a yellow-spotted millipede, Harpaphe haydeniana, while at Huddart Park with a group of kids from East Palo Alto.

The death scene must have lasted at least ten minutes, certainly time to get the camera and to interject myself into this life and death struggle. While my instinct was to free the millipede from the death threat, I felt that life must go on and that at times we must not interfere with the natural
flow of nature and allow things to come to their natural conclusion. What I observed was the female larviform of the adult phase of the Railroad Beetle. Males develop into beetle form but the females remain in larviform
I'm told these fellows are amphipods.  What do those massive front appendages do?
